.\" vi:set wm=5
.TH IMG2SIXEL 1 "Aug 2016"
.if n .ds Q \&"
.if n .ds U \&"
.if t .ds Q ``
.if t .ds U ''
.UC 4
.SH NAME
img2sixel \- image converter to DEC SIXEL graphics


.SH SYNOPSIS
.B img2sixel
[ \-\fIoptions\fP ] \fIimagefiles\fP
.br
.B img2sixel
[ \-\fIoptions\fP ] < \fIimagefiles\fP
.ta .5i 1.8i


.SH DESCRIPTION
\fIimg2sixel\fP converts various images into high quality DEC SIXEL image format.
.PP
The converter recognises the pseudo file target \(dqclipboard:\(dq in
addition to traditional paths.  Reading from \(dqclipboard:\(dq pulls the
most recent image or UTF-8 string payload from the desktop clipboard, while
writing to \(dqclipboard:\(dq publishes the generated SIXEL stream as
plain text.  Prefixes such as \(dqpng:clipboard:\(dq request that an
intermediate PNG snapshot is written to the clipboard instead of the raw
SIXEL sequence.  When reading, the converter probes for PNG data first,
falls back to TIFF, and finally consumes UTF-8 strings if no image payload
is present.


.SH "COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS"
\fIimg2sixel\fP has the following command-line options:
.PP
Arguments that select from a fixed set accept unique prefixes.  For
example, "\-s ave" resolves to "average", but "\-s a" is rejected because
it matches both "auto" and "average".
." Keep this list in the same order as `img2sixel -H`.
.TP 5
.B \-o, \-\-outfile
specify output file name (default:stdout).
Selecting a name ending in \(dq.png\(dq, the literal \(dqpng:-\(dq, or the
prefix \(dqpng:\(dq emits PNG data that reproduces the generated SIXEL
stream. The PNG keeps the palette indices so that each decoded pixel
mirrors the SIXEL quantizer. \(dqpng:-\(dq writes to standard output,
while \(dqpng:\fIpath\fP\(dq stores the PNG alongside the SIXEL
output. Using \(dq\-o output.png\(dq writes the PNG directly to that
path.
.TP 5
.B \-= \fICOUNT\fP, \-\-threads=\fICOUNT\fP
select the encoder thread count used for band parallelism.
The special value \fBauto\fP matches the hardware thread count.
Positive integers keep deterministic ordering with \fICOUNT\fP greater
than one enabling multi-threaded encoding while \fICOUNT\fP of one
preserves the sequential fallback path.
.TP 5
.B \-., \-\-precision=\fIMODE\fP
control the arithmetic precision used by the quantizers and dithering
pipelines.
.RS
.TP 5
.B auto
-> honor the \fBSIXEL_FLOAT32_DITHER\fP environment. This is the default
   and currently maps to the legacy 8bit backend when the variable is
   unset.
.TP 5
.B 8bit
-> force the historical integer pipeline regardless of the environment.
.TP 5
.B float32
-> request the experimental high-precision solvers without exporting the
   environment variable manually.
.RE
.TP 5
.B \-7, \-\-7bit-mode
generate a sixel image for 7bit terminals or printers (default).
.TP 5
.B \-8, \-\-8bit-mode
generate a sixel image for 8bit terminals or printers.
.TP 5
.B \-R, \-\-gri-limit
limit arguments of DECGRI('!') to 255.
.TP 5
.B \-6, \-\-6reversible
quantize every channel through the SIXEL reversible tone set so a decoded
image re-encoded with the same settings produces identical SIXEL bytes. Any
rounding error is pushed into the dithering stage.
.TP 5
.B \-p \fICOLORS\fP, \-\-colors=\fICOLORS\fP
specify number of colors to reduce the image to (default=256).
.TP 5
.B \-Q \fIMODEL\fP, \-\-quantize\-model=\fIMODEL\fP
select the palette solver. \fIMODEL\fP accepts \fBauto\fP,
\fBheckbert\fP, \fBkmeans\fP, or \fBkmedoids\fP. The \fBauto\fP setting preserves
the historical Heckbert median\-cut behaviour.
.br
The \fBkmeans\fP base value accepts suboptions using
\fBkmeans:key=value[:key=value...]\fP.
.br
Supported k-means suboptions:
.br
\fBinittype\fP (or short key \fBi\fP): \fBauto\fP, \fBnone\fP, \fBpca\fP.
.br
\fBthreshold\fP (or short key \fBt\fP): floating value in 0.0-0.5.
.br
\fBbinning\fP (or short key \fBb\fP): \fBauto\fP, \fBnone\fP, \fBhard\fP, \fBsoft\fP.
.br
\fBbinbits\fP (or short key \fBn\fP): integer value in 4-8.
.br
\fBmapping\fP (or short key \fBm\fP): \fBuniform\fP or \fBsrgb\fP.
.br
\fBsoftdist\fP (or short key \fBd\fP): \fBtrilinear\fP.
.br
\fBautoratio\fP (or short key \fBr\fP): integer value in 1-1048576.
.br
\fBfeedback\fP (or short key \fBf\fP): \fBoff\fP or \fBon\fP.
.br
The \fBkmedoids\fP base value accepts suboptions using
\fBkmedoids:key=value[:key=value...]\fP.
.br
Supported k-medoids suboptions:
.br
\fBalgo\fP (or short key \fBa\fP): \fBpam\fP, \fBclara\fP,
\fBclarans\fP, or \fBbanditpam\fP.
.br
\fBseed\fP (or short key \fBs\fP): integer value in 0-4294967295.
.TP 5
.B \-F \fIMODE\fP, \-\-final\-merge=\fIMODE\fP
control the post\-merge stage after palette construction. \fIMODE\fP accepts
\fBauto\fP, \fBnone\fP, or \fBward\fP. The default \fBauto\fP keeps
post\-merge reduction disabled so the behaviour matches \fBnone\fP unless
future heuristics request merging.
.TP 5
.B \-m \fIFILE\fP, \-\-mapfile=\fIFILE\fP
transform image colors to match this set of colors. Accepts image files
and palette files in Adobe Color Table (*.act), JASC/RIFF PAL (*.pal),
and GIMP Palette (*.gpl) formats. Use TYPE:PATH prefixes (act:, pal:,
pal\-jasc:, pal\-riff:, gpl:) to force a format. Without TYPE the
extension or file contents decide the palette type. Using TYPE:- reads
palette bytes from standard input (for example, gpl:-).
.TP 5
.B \-M \fIFILE\fP, \-\-mapfile\-output=\fIFILE\fP
export the computed palette. TYPE:PATH prefixes or file extensions
(.act, .pal, .gpl) select the output format. The .pal extension defaults
to JASC text output; use pal\-riff: for the RIFF layout. Writing to '-'
requires TYPE:PATH; TYPE:- directs the palette to standard output.
.TP 5
.B \-e, \-\-monochrome
output monochrome sixel image.
this option assumes the terminal background color is black.
.TP 5
.B \-k, \-\-insecure
allow to connect to SSL sites without certs
(enabled only when configured with a supported network backend)
.TP 5
.B \-i, \-\-invert
assume the terminal background color is white.
make sense only when -e option is given.
.TP 5
.B \-I, \-\-high-color
output 15bpp sixel image
.TP 5
.B \-u, \-\-use-macro
use DECDMAC and DECINVM sequences to optimize GIF animation rendering.
.TP 5
.B \-n \fIMACRONO\fP, \-\-macro-number=\fIMACRONO\fP
specify an number argument for DECDMAC and make terminal memorize
SIXEL image. No image is shown if this option is specified
.TP 5
.B \-C \fICOMPLEXIONSCORE\fP, \-\-complexion-score=\fICOMPLEXIONSCORE\fP
[[deprecated]] specify an number argument for the score of complexion correction.
\fICOMPLEXIONSCORE\fP must be 1 or more.
.TP 5
.B \-g, \-\-ignore-delay
render GIF animation without delay.
.TP 5
.B \-S, \-\-static
render animated GIF as a static image.
.TP 5
.B \-d \fIDIFFUSIONTYPE\fP, \-\-diffusion=\fIDIFFUSIONTYPE\fP
choose diffusion method which used with color reduction.
.br
\fIDIFFUSIONTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto     -> choose diffusion type automatically (default)
.br
none     -> do not diffuse
.br
fs       -> Floyd-Steinberg method
.br
atkinson -> Bill Atkinson's method
.br
jajuni   -> Jarvis, Judice & Ninke
.br
stucki   -> Stucki's method
.br
burkes   -> Burkes' method
.br
sierra1  -> Sierra Lite method
.br
sierra2  -> Sierra Two-row method
.br
sierra3  -> Sierra-3 method
.br
a_dither -> positionally stable arithmetic dither
.br
x_dither -> positionally stable arithmetic xor based dither
.br
bluenoise -> tileable blue-noise ordered dither
.br
lso2     -> libsixel method based on variable error diffusion tables,
.br
            optimized for size
.TP 5
.B \-y \fISCANTYPE\fP, \-\-diffusion\-scan=\fISCANTYPE\fP
choose scan order for error diffusion.
.br
\fISCANTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto -> choose scan order automatically (default)
.br
raster -> left-to-right scan on every line
.br
serpentine -> alternate direction on each line
.TP 5
.B \-Y \fICARRYTYPE\fP, \-\-diffusion\-carry=\fICARRYTYPE\fP
control carry buffers used during diffusion.
.br
\fICARRYTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto   -> choose carry mode automatically (default)
.br
direct -> write error back to pixel data immediately
.br
carry  -> accumulate error in workspace buffers before applying
.TP 5
.B \-f \fIFINDTYPE\fP, \-\-find\-largest=\fIFINDTYPE\fP
choose method for finding the largest dimension of median
cut boxes for splitting, make sense only when -p option
(color reduction) is specified.
.br
\fIFINDTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto -> choose finding method automatically (default)
.br
norm -> simply comparing the range in RGB space
.br
lum  -> transforming into luminosities before the comparison
.br
pca  -> split along the first principal component and cut at weighted median
.TP 5
.B \-s \fISELECTTYPE\fP, \-\-select\-color=\fISELECTTYPE\fP
choose the method for selecting representative color from each
median-cut box, make sense only when -p option (color reduction) is
specified.
.br
\fISELECTTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto     -> choose selecting method automatically (default)
.br
center   -> choose the center of the box
.br
average  -> calculate the color average into the box
.br
histogram -> similar with average but considers color histogram
.TP 5
.B \-c \fIREGION\fP, \-\-crop=\fIREGION\fP
crop source image to fit the specified geometry.
.br
REGION should be formatted as '%dx%d+%d+%d'.
.TP 5
.B \-w \fIWIDTH\fP, \-\-width=\fIWIDTH\fP
resize image to specified width.
.br
\fIWIDTH\fP is represented by the following syntax:
.br
auto       -> preserving aspect ratio (default)
.br
<number>%  -> scale width with given percentage
.br
<number>   -> scale width with pixel counts
.br
<number>c  -> scale width with terminal cell count
.br
<number>px -> scale width with pixel counts
.TP 5
.B \-h \fIHEIGHT\fP, \-\-height=\fIHEIGHT\fP
resize image to specified height.
.br
\fIHEIGHT\fP is represented by the following syntax
.br
auto       -> preserving aspect ratio (default)
.br
<number>%  -> scale height with given percentage
.br
<number>   -> scale height with pixel counts
.br
<number>c  -> scale height with terminal cell count
.br
<number>px -> scale height with pixel counts
.TP 5
.B \-r \fIRESAMPLINGTYPE\fP, \-\-resampling=\fIRESAMPLINGTYPE\fP
choose resampling method used with -w or -h option (scaling).
.br
\fIRESAMPLINGTYPE\fP is one of them:
.br
nearest  -> Nearest-Neighbor method
.br
gaussian -> Gaussian filter
.br
hanning  -> Hanning filter
.br
hamming  -> Hamming filter
.br
bilinear -> Bilinear filter (default)
.br
welsh    -> Welsh filter
.br
bicubic  -> Bicubic filter
.br
lanczos2 -> Lanczos-2 filter
.br
lanczos3 -> Lanczos-3 filter
.br
lanczos4 -> Lanczos-4 filter
.TP 5
.B \-q \fIQUALITYMODE\fP, \-\-quality=\fIQUALITYMODE\fP
select quality of color quanlization.
.br
\fIQUALITYMODE\fP is one of them:
.br
auto -> decide quality mode automatically (default)
.br
high -> high quality and low speed mode
.br
low  -> low quality and high speed mode
.br
full -> quality and careful speed mode
.TP 5
.B \-\~ \fILOOKUPPOLICY\fP, \-\-lookup\-policy=\fILOOKUPPOLICY\fP
choose histogram lookup width and backend.
.br
\fILOOKUPPOLICY\fP is one of them:
.br
auto      -> follow pixel depth to pick bucket size
.br
5bit      -> force classic 5-bit buckets
.br
6bit      -> force 6-bit RGB buckets (RGB inputs only)
.br
none      -> disable LUT caching and scan the palette directly
.br
certlut -> certified hierarchical LUT with zero approximation
.br
          The RGB cube is divided into 64x64x64 cells and refined only
          where necessary.  certlut reuses a single kd-tree built from
          the palette to certify the nearest and second nearest colours
          for every cell without scanning the full palette each time.
.br
eytzinger -> implicit binary tree lookup with a small neighbour scan
            (default).
.br
fhedt    -> Voronoi grid built via a 3-pass 3D EDT with optional
           boundary refinement at cell corners.
.br
vptree  -> VP-tree lookup built from palette entries with safe-distance
           pruning.
.PP
The \fInone\fP policy skips the lookup caches entirely so each pixel
comparison scans the palette directly.  This mirrors the behaviour that
`-q full` previously forced implicitly.
.PP
The \fIfhedt\fP grid honours the following environment variables:
.br
SIXEL_DITHER_LOOKUP_POLICY (auto, 5bit, 6bit, none, certlut, eytzinger,
fhedt, or vptree; default certlut)
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_PACKING (linear or morton; default linear) selects dense LUT
packing for 5bit/6bit lookups; other policies ignore it.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_RESOLUTION (64, 128, or 256; default 64)
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_REFINE (0 or 1; default 1) enables corner refinement
for boundary cells.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_USE_DIST2 (0 or 1; default 0 because recent measurements did
not show a consistent win) keeps per-voxel EDT distances so boundary voxels can
skip refinement when the center is already safely inside the Voronoi region.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_USE_CACHE (0 or 1; default 0 because the measured gain was
negligible; enable explicitly to re-evaluate) enables a small per-thread cache
keyed by voxel coordinates to speed up repeated lookups.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_SHARED (0 or 1; default 1) builds the grid once
before worker threads run and shares it read-only.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_CERTLUT_SHARED_INSTANCE (0 or 1; default 0) toggles whether
CERTLUT caches are shared across worker threads or rebuilt per worker.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_5BIT_SHARED_INSTANCE (0 or 1; default 1) controls whether the
5bit dense LUT is shared across workers without locks.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_6BIT_SHARED_INSTANCE (0 or 1; default 1) controls whether the
6bit dense LUT is shared across workers without locks.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_XY (adaptive default; clamped to the image size and
falling back to the adaptive choice on invalid input) sets the tile
width/height for the EDT passes.  The adaptive default shrinks tiles for
diverse palettes and grows them when the palette is biased to reduce
scheduling overhead.  Legacy SIXEL_FHEDT_TILE_XY remains accepted for
compatibility.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_DEPTH (adaptive default; same clamping as
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_XY) sets the tile depth for the EDT passes and follows
the same adaptive policy.  Legacy SIXEL_FHEDT_TILE_DEPTH remains accepted for
compatibility.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_FIRST_TOUCH (0 or 1; default 0) zeroes FHEDT tiles in
parallel before the EDT to let NUMA systems place pages on the worker that will
use them.  Legacy SIXEL_FHEDT_FIRST_TOUCH remains accepted for compatibility.
.br
SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_PIN_THREADS (0 or 1; default 0) pins FHEDT worker threads
once at startup to reduce migration; errors are ignored so portability is
preserved.  Legacy SIXEL_FHEDT_PIN_THREADS remains accepted for compatibility.
.br
SIXEL_LOG_PATH writes a JSON timeline log consumed by tools/timeline.py
when set; unset leaves logging disabled.
.br
SIXEL_LOG_LINES controls per-line logging when
SIXEL_LOG_PATH is set (0 disables line events, a positive integer logs
every Nth line; unset logs every line and may be heavy).
.TP 5
.B \-l \fILOOPMODE\fP, \-\-loop\-control=\fILOOPMODE\fP
select loop control mode for GIF animation.
.br
auto    -> honer the setting of GIF header (default)
.br
force   -> always enable loop
.br
disable -> always disable loop
.TP 5
.B \-T \fIFRAME_NO\fP, \-\-start-frame=\fIFRAME_NO\fP
set the animation start frame index for supported loaders.
.br
0 or positive values select absolute frame indices.
.br
negative values count from the end (-1 selects the last frame).
.TP 5
.B \-t \fIPALETTETYPE\fP, \-\-palette\-type=\fIPALETTETYPE\fP
select palette color space type.
.br
auto -> choose palette type automatically (default)
.br
hls  -> use HLS color space
.br
rgb  -> use RGB color space
.TP 5
.B \-b \fIBUILTINPALETTE\fP, \-\-builtin\-palette=\fIBUILTINPALETTE\fP
select built-in palette type
.br
xterm16    -> X default 16 color map
.br
xterm256   -> X default 256 color map
.br
vt340mono  -> VT340 monochrome map
.br
vt340color -> VT340 color map
.br
gray1      -> 1bit grayscale map
.br
gray2      -> 2bit grayscale map
.br
gray4      -> 4bit grayscale map
.br
gray8      -> 8bit grayscale map
.TP 5
.B \-E \fIENCODEPOLICY\fP, \-\-encode\-policy=\fIENCODEPOLICY\fP
select encoding policy
.br
auto -> choose encoding policy automatically (default)
.br
fast -> encode as fast as possible
.br
size -> encode to as small sixel sequence as possible
.TP 5
.B \-B \fIBGCOLOR\fP, \-\-bgcolor=\fIBGCOLOR\fP
.br
specify background color
.br
\fIBGCOLOR\fP is represented by the following syntax
.br
#rgb
.br
#rrggbb
.br
#rrrgggbbb
.br
#rrrrggggbbbb
.br
rgb:r/g/b
.br
rgb:rr/gg/bb
.br
rgb:rrr/ggg/bbb
.br
rgb:rrrr/gggg/bbbb
.TP 5
.B \-P, \-\-penetrate
[[deprecated]] penetrate GNU Screen using DCS pass-through sequence.
.TP 5
.B \-D, \-\-pipe\-mode
[[deprecated]] read source images from stdin continuously.
.TP 5
.B \-v, \-\-verbose
show debugging info and print the planner DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph).
.TP 5
.B \-L \fILIST\fP, \-\-loaders=\fILIST\fP
choose the loader priority order. \fILIST\fP is a comma separated
sequence of loader names. Each entry may be abbreviated by a unique prefix,
and a trailing "!" disables fallback loaders. The libpng, libjpeg, and
libwebp loaders accept
\fBorientation=on|off\fP (short form \fBo=\fP..., default on).
The libpng, libjpeg, libwebp, libtiff, and builtin loaders accept
\fBcms_engine=none|auto|builtin|lcms2|colorsync\fP (short form \fBe=\fP...,
default none).
The WIC loader also accepts suboptions such as \fBwic:ico_minsize=SIZE\fP to pick
the smallest ICO frame whose edge is at least SIZE.
.br
Recognized loader names (availability depends on the build):
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
libpng
.IP \(bu 2
libjpeg
.IP \(bu 2
libwebp
.IP \(bu 2
libtiff
.IP \(bu 2
librsvg
.IP \(bu 2
builtin
.IP \(bu 2
wic
.IP \(bu 2
coregraphics
.IP \(bu 2
gdk-pixbuf2
.IP \(bu 2
gd
.IP \(bu 2
quicklook
.IP \(bu 2
gnome-thumbnailer
.RE
.PP
For \fBlibrsvg\fP, SVG input is rasterized through Cairo and this loader
returns only RGB/RGBA frames. When no background color is specified and
non-opaque pixels are present, transparency is preserved in RGBA output;
otherwise the frame is emitted as RGB (including when \fB-B\fP requests
background compositing).
\fBUSE_PALETTE\fP and \fBREQCOLORS\fP are accepted for loader API
compatibility but are ignored by this backend; palette limits are applied by
the downstream quantizer.
.PP
By default, the librsvg path parses SVG bytes without assigning a base URI.
Relative external references (linked images, stylesheets, and similar assets)
are therefore not resolved.
Set \fBSIXEL_LOADER_LIBRSVG_ALLOW_RELATIVE_RESOURCES=1\fP to opt in to
file-path decode for local SVG files so relative references can resolve.
.PP
For local \fB.svgz\fP paths, the loader decodes through file-path mode even
when the opt-in is unset.
For gzip-compressed SVG data coming from stdin/pipe, this backend rejects the
input by default; set \fBSIXEL_LOADER_LIBRSVG_ALLOW_STDIN_SVGZ=1\fP to allow
temporary-file decode, or decompress first.
For decode-path diagnostics, set \fBSIXEL_TRACE_TOPIC=loader\fP; librsvg emits
\fBdecode_mode=data\fP, \fBdecode_mode=file\fP,
\fBdecode_mode=stdin_svgz_tempfile\fP, or
\fBdecode_mode=stdin_svgz_rejected\fP.
.PP
SVG loader comparison summary:
.nf
loader       transparency / -B              relative external refs      .svgz behavior                   palette
librsvg      keep RGBA without -B when      default disabled; opt-in    local .svgz path supported;      quantizer
             non-opaque pixels exist;       via SIXEL_LOADER_LIBRSVG_   stdin gzip opt-in via            stage
             otherwise RGB                  ALLOW_RELATIVE_RESOURCES=1
                                                                       SIXEL_LOADER_LIBRSVG_ALLOW_STDIN_SVGZ=1
gdk-pixbuf2  keep RGBA without -B when      backend-defined             backend-defined                  quantizer
             alpha exists; otherwise RGB                                                                      stage
coregraphics keep RGBA without -B when      backend-defined             backend-defined                  quantizer
             non-opaque pixels exist;                                                                          stage
             otherwise RGB
quicklook    keep RGBA without -B when      backend-defined             backend-defined                  quantizer
             non-opaque pixels exist;                                                                          stage
             otherwise RGB
.fi
.TP 5
.B \-# \fIENGINE\fP, \-\-cms\-engine=\fIENGINE\fP
set the default loader CMS backend for this process by exporting
\fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.br
\fIENGINE\fP accepts \fBnone\fP, \fBauto\fP, \fBbuiltin\fP,
\fBlcms2\fP, or \fBcolorsync\fP.
.br
\fBauto\fP prefers lcms2, then ColorSync (macOS), then builtin.
.TP 5
.B \-@, \-\-drcs
emit extended DRCS tiles instead of a regular SIXEL image (experimental).
This option accepts arguments in the form \fIMMV:CHARSET:PATH\fP. MMV picks the
Unicode mapping revision (0..2, default 2). CHARSET chooses the DRCS slot
(1-126 when MMV=0, 1-63 when MMV=1, 1-158 when MMV=2; default 1). PATH reroutes
tile data; use "-" to reuse standard output or leave it blank to discard tiles.
.br
This option requires the terminal to report pixel cell size via
.B TIOCGWINSZ
.TP 5
.B \-O, \-\-ormode
This option enables sixel output in "ormode". ormode is a SIXEL graphics
dialect originating from the netbsd/x68k console \fIite\fP and the twitter
client \fIsayaka\fP. It decomposes palette indices into bitplanes and
represents the index by overlaying planes via repaints, with the goal of
reducing output size.
.TP 5
.B \-X \fICOLORSPACE\fP, \-\-clustering\-colorspace=\fICOLORSPACE\fP
select palette clustering color space
.br
\fICOLORSPACE\fP is one of them:
.br
gamma  -> keep gamma encoded pixels (default)
.br
linear -> convert to linear RGB for clustering
.br
oklab -> cluster in OKLab uniform color space
.br
cielab -> cluster in CIELAB uniform color space
.br
din99d -> cluster in DIN99d uniform color space
.br
.TP 5
.B \-W \fICOLORSPACE\fP, \-\-working\-colorspace=\fICOLORSPACE\fP
select internal working color space
.br
\fICOLORSPACE\fP is one of them:
.br
gamma  -> keep gamma encoded pixels (default)
.br
linear -> convert to linear RGB for processing
.br
oklab -> operate in OKLab uniform color space for palette decisions
.br
cielab -> operate in CIELAB uniform color space for palette decisions
.br
din99d -> operate in DIN99d uniform color space for palette decisions
.br
.TP 5
.B \-U \fICOLORSPACE\fP, \-\-output\-colorspace=\fICOLORSPACE\fP
select output color space
.br
\fICOLORSPACE\fP is one of them:
.br
gamma   -> sRGB gamma encoded output (default)
.br
linear  -> linear RGB output
.br
smpte-c -> SMPTE-C gamma encoded output
.TP 5
.B \-1 \fITARGET\fP, \-\-show\-completion=\fITARGET\fP
print the requested completion script to standard output.
.br
\fITARGET\fP is one of them:
.br
bash -> emit the Bash completion script
.br
zsh -> emit the Zsh completion script
.br
all -> emit both scripts separated by comment banners.
The lookup order prefers files referenced through
\fIIMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_*\fP variables, then files installed under
\fIPKGDATADIR\fP, and finally falls back to the embedded script bundled with the
binary.
.TP 5
.B \-2 \fITARGET\fP, \-\-install\-completion=\fITARGET\fP
install completion scripts into user writable directories.
.br
\fITARGET\fP is one of them:
.br
bash -> install the Bash completion script
.br
zsh -> install the Zsh completion script
.br
all -> install both scripts.
Bash 4.x and later install to
\fI$HOME/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/img2sixel\fP while Bash 3.x
prefers \fI$HOME/.bash_completion.d/img2sixel\fP (created on demand). The
installer still refreshes the modern path when it already exists so distro
packages stay current. Zsh writes
to \fI$HOME/.zfunc/_img2sixel\fP and ensures the standard \fIfpath\fP and
\fIcompinit\fP lines are present inside \fI$HOME/.zshrc\fP. Use the
\fIIMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_HOME\fP override to test the installer against a custom
root.
.TP 5
.B \-3 \fITARGET\fP, \-\-uninstall\-completion=\fITARGET\fP
remove completion scripts previously installed by
\fB\-\-install\-completion\fP.
.br
\fITARGET\fP is one of them:
.br
bash -> remove the Bash completion script
.br
zsh -> remove the Zsh completion script
.br
all -> remove both scripts.
Each removal prints the outcome yet silently skips missing files so repeated
invocations remain idempotent.
.TP 5
.B \-V, \-\-version
show version and license info.
.br
The output also lists the loader backends available in the current build.
.TP 5
.B \-H, \-\-help
print help and list available loaders.


.SH "ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES"
\fIimg2sixel\fP honours the following environment variables:
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_OPTION_PREFIX_SUGGESTIONS
.br
toggle the prefix disambiguation hints emitted when a value matches more
than one option. Set to "1" (the default when unset) to print the candidate
list, or "0" to silence the diagnostic. Library embedders must opt in
explicitly.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_OPTION_FUZZY_SUGGESTIONS
.br
toggle the normalized Levenshtein suggestions that recommend the closest
option names after a typo. Set to "1" (the default when unset) to print the
hint list, or "0" to disable it. Library embedders must opt in explicitly.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_OPTION_PATH_SUGGESTIONS
.br
toggle the filesystem diagnostics that explain why a path could not be
resolved. Set to "1" to show the guidance, or "0" (the default) to suppress
it. The converter frontends keep the default disabled; library embedders must
opt in explicitly.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_STATUS_FORCE_COLORS
.br
force ANSI colorized diagnostics from status markup output. Set to "1" to
emit color sequences without relying on TTY detection.
.TP 5
.B IMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_BASH
.br
override the bash completion source path. When set, the completion commands
load content from the referenced file before consulting packaged defaults.
.TP 5
.B IMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_ZSH
.br
override the zsh completion source path. Shares the same priority rules as the
bash override.
.TP 5
.B IMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_DIR
.br
provide a directory that contains \fBbash/img2sixel\fP and \fBzsh/_img2sixel\fP
entries. The hybrid lookup checks this directory after the shell specific
override variables.
.TP 5
.B IMG2SIXEL_COMPLETION_HOME
.br
fake the home directory used during completion installation and removal. This
is helpful for testing the workflow inside disposable directories.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_ABORT_TRACE
.br
dump abort backtraces when \fIimg2sixel\fP terminates abnormally. Defaults to
auto (enabled). Set to "0"/"false"/"off" to disable explicit traces; any other
non-empty value forces them on.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_NO_ABORT_TRACE
.br
legacy inverse toggle for abort tracing. Any non-zero/true value suppresses
dumps while "0"/"false"/"off" keeps tracing enabled.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_BGCOLOR
.br
specify background color.
.br
overrided by -B(--bgcolor) option.
.br
represented by the following syntax:
.br
#rgb
.br
#rrggbb
.br
#rrrgggbbb
.br
#rrrrggggbbbb
.br
rgb:r/g/b
.br
rgb:rr/gg/bb
.br
rgb:rrr/ggg/bbb
.br
rgb:rrrr/gggg/bbbb
.br
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_OSC11_BG_QUERY
.br
enable loader-side OSC11 background color query when no background color was
provided. Only the exact value \(dq1\(dq enables probing. Default is off.
\fIimg2sixel\fP sets this variable to \(dq1\(dq only when it is unset.
When probing succeeds, the loader treats the returned background as gamma.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_OSC11_BG_QUERY_TIMEOUT_MS
.br
timeout in milliseconds for the loader OSC11 background color query wait.
Defaults to 50. Invalid values fall back to 50.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_ANIMATION_HIDE_CURSOR
.br
hide the terminal cursor with DECTCEM (\fBESC[?25l\fP) while animated frames
are emitted to a tty output. Only the exact value \(dq1\(dq enables this
behavior. Default is off. \fIimg2sixel\fP sets this variable to \(dq1\(dq
only when it is unset.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_COLORS
.br
specify number of colors to reduce the image to (default=256).
.br
overrided by -p(--colors) option.
.br
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_FLOAT32_DITHER
.br
prefer the float32 quantization path. Any non-empty string other than 0, off,
false, or no enables the high-precision pipeline.
.br
For SVG decoded via \fBlibrsvg\fP, the source raster remains cairo ARGB32
(8-bit per channel); float32 improves downstream processing precision but does
not recover higher source bit depth from the loader.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PLANNER_RESIZE_PRECISION_MODE
.br
force the resize precision planner. Accepts 1 (preserve integer buffers), 2
(linear float workspace), or 3 (float32 working colorspace). Defaults follow
the precision and working-colorspace choices described under
\fB\-\.\fP/\fB\-\-precision\fP and \fB\-W\fP/\fB\-\-working\-colorspace\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_THREADS
.br
override the encoder thread count used for band processing.
.br
Accept positive integers or the string \(dqauto\(dq to match the
hardware thread count.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_PIN_THREADS
.br
pin pipeline worker threads to their initial CPUs (0 or 1; default 1).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_PARALLEL_THREADS_MAX
.br
cap the number of dither workers when band parallelism is active. Accepts
positive integers.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_PARALLEL_BAND_WIDTH
.br
override the band height assigned to each dither worker. Values are rounded to
a multiple of six scanlines.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_PARALLEL_BAND_OVERWRAP
.br
set overlap between adjacent dither bands to smooth seams. Accepts non-negative
integers.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_STRENGTH
.br
scale bluenoise ordered dither strength when \fB\-d bluenoise\fP is set.
Accepts 0.0-2.0; defaults to 0.055.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_A_DITHER_STRENGTH
.br
override positional a_dither strength. Defaults to 0.150 when unset.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_X_DITHER_STRENGTH
.br
override positional x_dither strength. Defaults to 0.100 when unset.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_PHASE
.br
phase offset for bluenoise tiles when \fB\-d bluenoise\fP is set. Format is
\(dqox,oy\(dq with signed integers; defaults to 0,0.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_SEED
.br
seed used to derive a bluenoise phase when \fB\-d bluenoise\fP is set and
\fBSIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_PHASE\fP is unset.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_CHANNEL
.br
choose bluenoise channel mode when \fB\-d bluenoise\fP is set. Accepts mono
(shared) or rgb (independent) samples; defaults mono.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_BLUENOISE_SIZE
.br
bluenoise tile size when \fB\-d bluenoise\fP is set. Only 64 is embedded;
other values fall back to 64.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_SCALE_PARALLEL_MIN_BYTES
.br
delay parallel resize until the frame exceeds this byte threshold. Default 0
keeps eager threading.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PARALLEL_FACTOR
.br
override the row span assigned to each resize worker. Accepts positive
integers.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_COLORSPACE_PARALLEL_MIN_PIXELS
.br
defer RGBFLOAT32 colorspace fan-out until the frame reaches this pixel
count. Defaults to 65537 pixels to avoid eager splitting on small images.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PARALLEL_SKEW
.br
bias parallel decode spans by +/-20%% so trailing workers take a larger share.
Defaults to 0 (balanced).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_SIMD_LEVEL
.br
force SIMD selection. Accepts auto, none/scalar, sse2, avx, or neon.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_THUMBNAILER_HINT_SIZE
.br
adjust the thumbnail target size used by loader helpers. Accepts positive
integers; defaults to the built-in hint.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_PRIORITY_LIST
.br
override the default loader priority. Accepts the same comma separated
names recognised by \fB-L\fP/\fB--loaders\fP, including prefix matches and
the trailing "!" suffix. The environment setting is ignored when the
command-line option is present.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_BACKGROUND_COLORSPACE
.br
set how loader background colors are interpreted during alpha composition.
accepts "gamma" (default) or "linear".
ignored when OSC11 query supplies the background color.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_ORIENTATION
.br
set the default EXIF orientation handling for libjpeg/libpng/libwebp
loaders. Accepts "on"/"off" (preferred) and "1"/"0" aliases.
defaults to on.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBJPEG_ORIENTATION
.br
override EXIF orientation handling for the libjpeg loader.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_ORIENTATION\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBPNG_ORIENTATION
.br
override EXIF orientation handling for the libpng loader.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_ORIENTATION\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBWEBP_ORIENTATION
.br
override EXIF orientation handling for the libwebp loader.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_ORIENTATION\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_ANIMATION_START_FRAME_NO
.br
set the animation start frame index for supported animation loaders.
0 or positive values select absolute indexes from the first frame.
negative values count from the end; \-1 selects the last frame.
out-of-range indexes fail with an error.
the index is applied only on the first playback loop, and later loops
decode from frame 0.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE
.br
select the default loader CMS backend. Accepts "none", "auto", "builtin",
"lcms2", or "colorsync".
"auto" prefers lcms2, then ColorSync (macOS), then builtin.
overrided by \fB-#\fP/\fB--cms\-engine\fP option.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_BUILTIN_CMS_ENGINE
.br
override the builtin loader CMS backend.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBPNG_CMS_ENGINE
.br
override the libpng loader CMS backend.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBJPEG_CMS_ENGINE
.br
override the libjpeg loader CMS backend.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBWEBP_CMS_ENGINE
.br
override the libwebp loader CMS backend.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_LIBTIFF_CMS_ENGINE
.br
override the libtiff loader CMS backend.
overrides \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_ENGINE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_CMS_RENDERING_INTENT
.br
override the lcms2 rendering-intent fallback order used by PNG loader CMS
conversion. Accepts comma-separated values from "perceptual",
"relative" ("relative_colorimetric"), "saturation", and "absolute"
("absolute_colorimetric"). Append "!" to disable default fallback intents.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_CMS_RENDERING_INTENT
.br
legacy alias for \fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_RENDERING_INTENT\fP. Used only when
\fBSIXEL_LOADER_CMS_RENDERING_INTENT\fP is unset.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOADER_WIC_ICO_MINSIZE
.br
default minimum edge used by \fBwic:ico_minsize\fP when no suboption is
provided. Positive integers are accepted.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LODER_WIC_ICO_MINSIZE
.br
legacy alias for \fBSIXEL_LOADER_WIC_ICO_MINSIZE\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_SAMPLE_TARGET
.br
request a specific sample count for palette estimation. Positive integers
override automatic sizing.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_OVERSPLIT_FACTOR
.br
scale the provisional palette before the final merge (1.0-3.0,
default 1.81).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_FINAL_MERGE_ADDITIONAL_LLOYD_ITER_COUNT
.br
run Lloyd refinement after the final merge stage. Accepts 0-30.
Defaults to 3 iterations.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_ITER_COUNT_MAX
.br
cap the primary k-means Lloyd refinement (1-30, default 20).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_THRESHOLD
.br
delta threshold for k-means refinement (0.0-0.5, default 0.125).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_INITTYPE
.br
choose k-means seed selection: auto, pca, or none (default auto).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_BINNING
.br
k-means histogram pre-binning mode: auto, none, hard, or soft. Default auto
selects soft when sample density is high.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_BINBITS
.br
k-means histogram bits per channel (4-8, default 6).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_MAPPING
.br
k-means histogram mapping space: uniform or srgb (default uniform).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_SOFTDIST
.br
k-means soft-binning kernel. Currently supports trilinear.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_AUTORATIO
.br
k-means auto-binning density ratio threshold (1-1048576, default 32).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_KMEANS_FEEDBACK
.br
k-means residual histogram feedback switch: off or on (default off).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_LUMIN_FACTOR_R
.br
override the luminosity coefficient for red (0.0-1.0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_LUMIN_FACTOR_G
.br
override the luminosity coefficient for green (0.0-1.0). The blue
coefficient becomes 1 - R - G; negative results ignore both overrides.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_CHANNEL_FACTOR_L
.br
emphasise L* weight in Lab-family distances before snapping (0.0-1.0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_MERGE_CHANNEL_FACTOR_L
.br
emphasise L* weight during final merge distances independently of snap tuning
(0.0-1.0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_DISABLE_TABLES
.br
disable palette expansion lookup tables and exercise the shift-based fallback
used for testing. Non-zero values skip table initialisation.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_SNAP_TARGET_POLICY
.br
control palette snap target search. Accepts "reversible" for legacy fixed
points or "nearest"/"auto" for nearby fixed points in the working colorspace.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_SNAP_TIMING_POLICY
.br
decide when snaps run: "once", "polish", "merge", "resolve", or "all".
Defaults to "once".
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_SNAP_APPROACH_RATE
.br
blend factor (0.0-1.0) toward the snap target; 1.0 snaps fully, lower values
ease toward the target.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_PALETTE_SNAP_CHANNEL_FACTOR_L
.br
weight L* relative to a/b* when snapping in Lab-family colorspaces.
Accepts 0.0-1.0, default 0.85.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_DITHER_LOOKUP_POLICY
.br
select palette lookup policy (auto, 5bit, 6bit, none, certlut,
eytzinger, fhedt, or vptree).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_PACKING
.br
select dense LUT packing for 5bit/6bit lookup (linear or morton; default
linear; other policies ignore it).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_RESOLUTION
.br
choose FHEDT grid resolution (64, 128, or 256; default 64).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_REFINE
.br
enable corner refinement on FHEDT boundary cells (0 or 1; default 1).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_USE_DIST2
.br
reuse EDT distances to skip corner refinement (0 or 1; default 0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_USE_CACHE
.br
enable a small FHEDT lookup cache keyed by voxel coordinates (0 or 1; default
0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_SHARED
.br
share the FHEDT grid between workers after building it once (0 or 1; default
1).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_CERTLUT_SHARED_INSTANCE
.br
share the CERTLUT cache across threads (0 or 1; default 0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_5BIT_SHARED_INSTANCE
.br
share the 5bit LUT across threads without locks (0 or 1; default 1).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_6BIT_SHARED_INSTANCE
.br
share the 6bit LUT across threads without locks (0 or 1; default 1).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_XY
.br
set FHEDT tile width/height; adaptive defaults shrink tiles for diverse
palettes and grow them for skewed palettes.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_DEPTH
.br
set FHEDT tile depth; follows the same adaptive policy as
\fISIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_XY\fP.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_FIRST_TOUCH
.br
zero FHEDT tiles before the EDT so NUMA systems can place pages on the worker
that will consume them (0 or 1; default 0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_PIN_THREADS
.br
pin FHEDT worker threads at startup to reduce migration (0 or 1; default 0).
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_FHEDT_TILE_XY
.br
compatibility alias for \fBSIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_XY\fP with identical
behaviour and adaptive defaults.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_FHEDT_TILE_DEPTH
.br
compatibility alias for \fBSIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_TILE_DEPTH\fP with identical
behaviour and adaptive defaults.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_FHEDT_FIRST_TOUCH
.br
compatibility alias for \fBSIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_FIRST_TOUCH\fP with identical
behaviour and defaults.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_FHEDT_PIN_THREADS
.br
compatibility alias for \fBSIXEL_LOOKUP_FHEDT_PIN_THREADS\fP with identical
behaviour and defaults.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOG_PATH
.br
write a JSON timeline for FHEDT or LUT builds when set.
.TP 5
.B SIXEL_LOG_LINES
.br
log every Nth line in the timeline; 0 disables line events.


.SH Image loaders

\fIimg2sixel\fP includes two or more image decoder components.

.TP 5
.B stb_image

\fIlibsixel\fP includes \fIstb_image\fP, a public domain image loader.
.br
\fIimg2sixel\fP uses it as default built-in image decoder.
It can decode almost all images. but a few images can not be decoded by its limitations.

.B Supported source formats:
   JPEG baseline & progressive (12 bpc/arithmetic not supported, same as stock IJG lib)
   PNG 1/2/4/8/16-bit-per-channel
   TGA (not sure what subset, if a subset)
   BMP non-1bpp, non-RLE
   PSD (composited view only, no extra channels)
   PIC (Softimage PIC)
   PNM (PPM and PGM binary only)

.B Limitations:
   no 12-bit-per-channel JPEG
   no JPEGs with arithmetic coding / JPEG 2000
   no 1-bit BMP

.TP 5
.B libpng

   If \fIlibpng\fP library is linked at compile time, \fIimg2sixel\fP uses it for decoding PNG image.

.TP 5
.B libjpeg

   If \fIlibjpeg\fP library is linked at compile time, \fIimg2sixel\fP uses it for decoding JPEG image.

.TP 5
.B libtiff

   If \fIlibtiff\fP library is linked at compile time, \fIimg2sixel\fP uses it for decoding TIFF image.

.TP 5
.B gdk-pixbuf2

   If \fIgdk-pixbuf2\fP library is linked at compile time, \fIimg2sixel\fP uses it automatically in some cases.

.TP 5
.B GD

   If \fIGD\fP library is linked at compile time, \fIimg2sixel\fP uses it automatically in some cases.

.TP 5
.B libsixel

   \fIimg2sixel\fP can load SIXEL as source image format, because it uses \fIlibsixel\fP as a SIXEL image decoder.


.SH HISTORY

Former SIXEL encoders(such as \fIppmtosixel\fP) are mainly designed for dot-matrix printers.
They minimize the amount of printer-head movement distance.
But nowadays this method did not represent the best performance for displaying sixel data on terminal emulators.
Encoded SIXEL data for VT-2xx/VT-3xx terminals were found in 80's Usenet,
But the technology of how to create them seems to be lost.

\fBkmiya's sixel\fP(kmiya,2014) introduces an efficient encoding method which is re-designed for terminal emulators to
optimize the overhead of transporting SIXEL with keeping compatibility with former SIXEL terminal.
Now \fIlibsixel\fP and \fIImageMagick\fP's sixel coder follow it.

\fBAraki Ken\fP, known as the maintainer of mlterm, proposed the method for more compressed SIXEL encoding.
Now \fIlibsixel\fP adopted that method.
\fBAraki Ken\fP describes about the way to generate high quality SIXEL.

See http://mlterm.sourceforge.net/libsixel.pdf(in Japanese).


